-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - Nov 17
-- By Yimou Lee
-- Sun Nov 16, 2014 08:52PM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Nov 17 (Reuters) - Following are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Monday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST - Beijing's crackdown on fake trade seems to have made little difference as the recent surge in mainland exports of precious metals and jewellery and the discrepancy in Hong Kong-related trade figures signal the problem of inflated invoicing is back. (http://bit.ly/1tZgfZm) - GCL-Poly Energy Holdings <3800.HK>, the world's largest maker of solar panel raw materials polysilicon and solar wafers, has surprised investors by unveiling a plan to sell a major chunk of its business - wafer production - to a third party that may sell it to GCL's largest shareholder. (http://bit.ly/1sW81C6) - Tianhe Chemicals Group <1619.HK> on Sunday rejected an article by the Associated Press that said reporters at the US news agency had uncovered significant discrepancies between financial records and what the company told investors during its $654 million stock offering earlier this year. (http://bit.ly/1uC5Esj) - China VLCC, a joint venture between China Merchants Group and Sinotrans & CSC Group, will operate about 40 very large crude carriers - supertankers each measuring more than 300 metres and able to carry 2 million barrels of crude. (http://bit.ly/11c1Y4V)  THE STANDARD  - Pre-launch readiness tests for the Shanghai Hong Kong Stock Connect have cast light on how quickly the daily trading quotas will be used up. In Shanghai, the daily southbound trading quota of 10.5 billion yuan ($1.71 billion) was used up within the first half hour after the simulation test began at the weekend, mainland media reported. (http://bit.ly/11h7GSZ)  - Chinese mobile and web games developer Feiyu Technology International passed its listing hearing on Thursday and will open the retail book on November 25 for a main board listing seeking as much as HK$1.5 billion. Its debut is slated for December 5, a source said. (http://bit.ly/14wpjAr)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  - Turnover at the Hong Kong stock exchange <0388.HK>, which had an average daily turnover of HK$83.7 billion last week, is expected to cross more than HK$100 billion after the landmark "through-train" scheme that connects equity markets in Hong Kong and Shanghai.  - At least 12 companies, including China General Nuclear Power Group and Hong Kong Airlines, are planning initial public offerings in the Hong Kong Stock exchange by the end of this year, raising more than HK$47.3 billion, according to market sources. - Weekend new home sales reached a 6-week high with more than 430 flats sold over the weekend as developers continued to launch new projects with discounts.  SING TAO DAILY - The percentage of those who did not support the Occupy movement surpassed that of supporters, according to a survey by Hong Kong's Chinese University. It also showed almost 70 percent of respondents believed protesters should leave now.